<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<h3
 style="margin: 0.1pt 0in; font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">Tentative
Reading
List:</h3>
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<small style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><small><br>
</small></small>
<h3
 style="margin: 0.1pt 0in; font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);"><small>This
will
surely
evolve
significantly.
The
following
papers
are
from
the
theoretical
CS
and
algorithms
literature,
or
papers
recommended
by
colleagues.</small></h3>
<ul style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
  <li>Introductory Readings</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Required: <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/scipm_ieee_computer.pdf">Overview</a>
of
the
final report for the NSF <a href="http://scipm.cs.vt.edu/">Workshop
on
the Science of Power Management</a>. <br>
    </li>
    <li>Optional:
The <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/SciPM-ReportToNSF-Web.pdf">final
report</a> <br>
    </li>
  </ul>
</ul>
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<ul style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
  <li>Surveys on Algorithmic Power Management</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Very early survey: <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/sigactreview.pdf">Algorithmic
Problems
in
Power
Management















      </a>by Irani and Pruhs, 2005.<br>
    </li>
    <li>Relatively recent survey: <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/AlbersSurvey.pdf">Algorithms
for
Energy
Saving















      </a>by Susanne Albers, 2009.</li>
    <li><a
 href="http://cacm.acm.org/magazines/2010/5/87271-energy-efficient-algorithms/fulltext">Energy
Efficient
Algorithms,</a> Briefer version of the above survey written
for a general audience in May CACM 2010 by Susanne Albers.<br>
    </li>
  </ul>
</ul>
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<ul style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
  <li>Competitiveness Results on Speed Scaling</li>
  <ul>
    <li>
      <p><span class="headNavBlueXLarge2"> Modeling</span></p>
    </li>
    <ul>
      <li><span class="headNavBlueXLarge2"><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/p191-butts.pdf">A
Static
Power
Model
for
Architects</a> by J. Adam Butts and Gurindar S.
Sohi, </span> <span class="mediumb-text">ACM/IEEE international
symposium on
Microarchitecture 2000. (<a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/micro00-staticpower.pdf">Slides</a>,
















        <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/ButtsSohiNotes.txt">notes</a>)
This
explains
how
to
model
power.</span></li>
    </ul>
    <li>
      <p><span class="headNavBlueXLarge2">Deadline Scheduling</span></p>
    </li>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <p><span class="headNavBlueXLarge2"><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/yds.pdf">A
scheduling model for reduced CPU energy</a> by Francis Yao, Demers and
Shenker, FOCS 1995. The first speed scaling paper in the algorithmic
community.</span></p>
      </li>
      <li> <strong><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/BKP.pdf">Speed
scaling to manage energy
and
temperature </a><span style="font-weight: normal;">by Nikhil Bansal,
Tracy Kimbrel and Kirk Pruhs, FOCS
2004 and JACM 2007. This continues the story started in Yao, Demers and
Shenker. Introduced amortized local competitivess and temperature using
Newton's law of cooling.<br>
        </span></strong></li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/latin2008.pdf">Average
Rate
Speed
Scaling</a> by
Nikhil Bansal, David P. Bunde, Ho-Leung Chan, Kirk Pruhs, LATIN 2008.
Tight analysis of the AVR algorithm using amortized local
competitiveness.<br>
      </li>
      <li> <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/icalp2009.pdf">Improved
Bounds
for
Speed
Scaling
in
Devices
Obeying
the
Cube-Root
Rule</a> by Nikhil Bansal, Ho-Leung Chan,
Dmitriy Katz and Kirk Pruhs, ICALP 2009.
This gives the best known upper and lower bounds on the competitive
ratio for the original Yao et al
problem.</li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/jos-ahmed.pdf">An
experimental
comparison
of
speed
scaling
algorithms
with
a
deadline
feasibility
constraint</a> by
Abousamra, Bunde and Pruhs. Shows that competitive analysis agrees with
experimental evaluation for classic deadline feasibility problem<br>
      </li>
      <li> <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/solarcell.pdf">Speed
Scaling
with
a
Solar
Cell















        </a>by
Nikhil
Bansal,
Ho-Leung
Chan,
Kirk
Pruhs,&nbsp;
AAIM
2008.
Extends
YDS
style
results
to
the
setting
that
the
energy
comes
from
a
rejuvinative
source
such
as
a
solar
cell</li>
      <li> <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/icalp2009boundedspeed.pdf">Scheduling
for
Speed
Bounded
Processors















        </a>by Nikhil Bansal,
Ho-Leung Chan,
Tak Wah Lam,
Lap-Kei Lee, ICALP 2008. Considers bounding the speed and then
optimizing throughput</li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/Chroback.pdf">Algorithms
for
Temperature-Aware
Task
Scheduling
in
Microprocessor
Systems</a> by Marek Chrobak, Christoph
Durr, Mathilde Hurand, and Julien Robert, AAIM
2008. Assume the speed scaling is controlled by hardware that throttles
the speed when the chip gets too hot.</li>
    </ul>
    <li> Flow and energy</li>
    <ul>
      <li>&nbsp;<a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/SWAT2004.pdf">Getting
the
best
response
for
your
erg</a>, by Kirk Pruhs, Patchrawat Uthaisombut and Gerhard
Woeginger, SWAT 2004 and TALG 2008. Introduces optimizing flow subject
to an energy constraint and gives offline algorithm.</li>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="erg.jnlp">Animation</a>
(<a href="erg-src.zip">source code</a>) by <a
 href="http://www.cs.mcgill.ca/%7Eyzwols/">Yori Zwols</a><br>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/a49-albers.pdf">&nbsp;Efficient
algorithms
for
flow
time
minimization</a> by Susanne Albers and Hiroshi
Fujiwara, STACS 2006 and TALG 2007. Introduces flow plus energy and
gives competitive algorithm for the case of unit work jobs using global
analysis.<br>
      </li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/BPS.pdf">Speed
scaling for weighted flow time</a> by
Nikhil Bansal, Kirk Pruhs and Cliff Stein, SODA 2007. Gives first
compeitive algorithm for general jobs.<br>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <ul>
      <li> <a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/SODA2009.pdf">Speed
scaling
with
an
arbitrary
power
function</a> by Nikhil Bansal, Ho-Leung Chan and Kirk Pruhs, SODA 2009.
This paper introduces general power functions and shows how to extend
flow+energy results to general power functions.<br>
      </li>
      <ul>
        <li>&nbsp;<a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/mama09.pdf">Optimal
speed
scaling
under
arbitrary
power
functions















          </a>by Lachlan L. H. Andrew, Adam Wierman
and Ao Tang. Improves competitive ratio from 3 to 2.<br>
        </li>
      </ul>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/stacs2009.pdf">Nonclairvoyant
Speed
Scaling
for
Flow
and
Energy















        </a>by Ho-Leung Chan, Jeff Edmonds, Tak Wah Lam, Lap-Kei
Lee, Alberto Marchetti-Spaccamela, Kirk Pruhs. STACS 2009. First paper
to consider nonclairvoyant algorithms.<br>
      </li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/SPAA2009.pdf">Speed
scaling
of
processes
with
arbitrary
speedup
curves
on
a
multiprocessor</a> by Ho-Leung Chan, Jeff Edmonds
and Kirk Pruhs, SPAA 2009. Considers nonclairvoyant scheduling of jobs
with varying degrees of parallelizability on a multiprocessor</li>
      <li><a href="spaa2008.pdf">Competitive Non-migratory Scheduling
for Flow Time and Energy </a>by Tak-Wah Lam, Lap-Kei Lee, Isaac K. K.
To and Prudence W. H. Wong &nbsp; in SPAA 2008. Gives an assignment
algorithm for multiprocessors.</li>
      <li>Sleep with Guilt and Work Faster to Minimize Flow Plus Energy<br>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <li>Profit Maximization</li>
    <ul>
      <li>How to schedule when you have to buy your energy by Pruhs and
Stein<br>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <li>There are more algorithmic speed scaling papers, but these
papers should include all the most important ones and a reasonable
sampling of the rest. <br>
    </li>
  </ul>
</ul>
<br style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
<ul style="font-family: Comic Sans MS; color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
  <li>Theoretical Results on Power/Shut down</li>
  <ul>
    <li>Transition to power saving states</li>
    <ul>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/p325-irani-1.pdf">Online
Strategies
for
Dynamic
Power
Management
in
Systems
with
Multiple
Power
Saving
States</a> by
Sandy Irani, Sandeep Shukla and Rajesh Gupta, ACM Transactions on
Embedded Computing Systems 2003.<br>
      </li>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/Augustine.pdf">Optimal
Power-Down
Strategies















        </a>by
John Augustine, Sandy Irani and Chaitanya Swamy, FOCS 2004 and SICOMP
2008. (<a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/dpmslides-short.ppt">slides</a>
from Chaitanya Swamy)</li>
      <li><a href="VitterSpindown.pdf">Adaptive disk spindown via
optimal rent-to-buy in probabilistic environments</a> by Krishnan, Long
and Vitter, Algorithmica.</li>
    </ul>
    <li>Speed scaling and shutdown</li>
    <ul>
      <li><a
 href="http://www.cs.pitt.edu/%7Ekirk/cs3150spring2010/power_soda-1.pdf">Algorithms
for
Power
Savings</a> by
Sandy Irani, Sandeep Shukla and Rajesh Gupta, SODA 2003 and TALG 2007. </li>
      <li><a href="icalp09.pdf">Sleep with Guilt and Work Faster to
Minimize Flow Plus Energy</a> byTak-Wah Lam, Lap-Kei Lee, Hing-Fung
Ting, Isaac K. To, Prudence W. Wong in ICALP 2009.<br>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <li>Scheduling for gaps/idleness<br>
    </li>
    <ul>
      <li><a
